{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01NDJw88FkR3KyFYiU6EFXWK","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 11 → 12 Improvement Plan\n     2→\n     3→## Summary\n     4→\n     5→One failure: **CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM** → returns `\"CHLEBEK\"`.\n     6→\n     7→Root cause: bilingual detection false positive. A book category header at position 0 (\"Lato | Dania główne\") is mistaken for a mixed-case recipe title, causing the real ALL_CAPS title to be suppressed. Three changes fix this — one primary and two defense-in-depth.\n     8→\n     9→---\n    10→\n    11→## Failure 1: CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\n    12→\n    13→### Root Cause Analysis\n    14→\n    15→The bilingual detection block (lines 409–431) looks for a mixed-case candidate at position 0, then checks if nearby ALL_CAPS candidates (positions 1–2) are semantically similar. If similarity > 0.4, the ALL_CAPS candidates are suppressed from threshold calculation.\n    16→\n    17→**What goes wrong:**\n    18→\n    19→1. `\"Lato | Dania główne\"` (book category header meaning \"Summer | Main dishes\") sits at position 0, is mixed-case, and passes the `prePos0` check.\n    20→\n    21→2. `\"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\"` at position 1 is ALL_CAPS. Cosine similarity between a food-category phrase and a food-recipe title exceeds 0.4 in MiniLM's embedding space — the food domain clusters tightly.\n    22→\n    23→3. The real title gets suppressed from `scoredForThreshold`, which means it never enters `selected`.\n    24→\n    25→4. **Cascading failure**: Every downstream safety mechanism is gated on the full title being in `selected`:\n    26→   - Prefix removal (line 458): `selected.some(s => s.text === firstStructuralHeading.text)` → false\n    27→   - Pre-dedup section filter (line 516): `hasLongerParent` checks only `selected` → false\n    28→   - Dedup has nothing to compare `\"CHLEBEK\"` against\n    29→   - Multi-title guard returns `\"CHLEBEK\"` as sole survivor\n    30→\n    31→### Fix A (Primary): Exclude pipe-separated lines from candidates\n    32→\n    33→**Rationale:** Lines containing `|` are book category/chapter headers (\"Season | Category\", \"Appetizers | Vegetarian\"), never recipe titles. This is a near-universal typographic convention in cookbooks. Filtering them removes the false trigger entirely.\n    34→\n    35→**Change:** Add a pipe-separator check to `passesHardFilters()` in `title-extractor.ts`.\n    36→\n    37→**Before (line 138–148):**\n    38→```typescript\n    39→function passesHardFilters(text: string): boolean {\n    40→  if (text.length < 3 || text.length > 80) return false;\n    41→  if (looksLikeIngredient(text)) return false;\n    42→  if (startsWithNumber(text)) return false;\n    43→  if (looksLikeMetadata(text)) return false;\n    44→  if (isLikelyGarbled(text)) return false;\n    45→  const words = text.trim().split(/\\s+/);\n    46→  if (words.length === 1 && NON_TITLE_WORDS.has(text.trim().toLowerCase())) return false;\n    47→  return true;\n    48→}\n    49→```\n    50→\n    51→**After:**\n    52→```typescript\n    53→function passesHardFilters(text: string): boolean {\n    54→  if (text.length < 3 || text.length > 80) return false;\n    55→  if (looksLikeIngredient(text)) return false;\n    56→  if (startsWithNumber(text)) return false;\n    57→  if (looksLikeMetadata(text)) return false;\n    58→  if (isLikelyGarbled(text)) return false;\n    59→  // Pipe-separated lines are book category/chapter headers, not recipe titles\n    60→  if (text.includes(\" | \")) return false;\n    61→  const words = text.trim().split(/\\s+/);\n    62→  if (words.length === 1 && NON_TITLE_WORDS.has(text.trim().toLowerCase())) return false;\n    63→  return true;\n    64→}\n    65→```\n    66→\n    67→**Impact:** `\"Lato | Dania główne\"` is excluded from candidates entirely. Bilingual detection has no position-0 mixed-case candidate → doesn't fire → `\"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\"` stays in the pool → downstream mechanisms work correctly → correct title returned.\n    68→\n    69→**Risk:** Extremely low. Recipe titles do not contain ` | ` (space-pipe-space). The pattern is specific to book section headers, table of contents entries, and similar structural elements. No existing test case is affected.\n    70→\n    71→---\n    72→\n    73→### Fix B (Defense in depth): Guard bilingual suppression against structural headings\n    74→\n    75→**Rationale:** Even after Fix A, a future input could have a different kind of non-title at position 0 that triggers bilingual detection. The structural heading is the algorithm's highest-confidence title signal — bilingual detection (a speculative heuristic) should never override it.\n    76→\n    77→**Change:** In the bilingual detection block (lines 422–429), add a guard that preserves `firstStructuralHeading` (and any candidate starting with it) even when suppression fires.\n    78→\n    79→**Before (lines 422–429):**\n    80→```typescript\n    81→if (translationCandidates.length > 0) {\n    82→  scoredForThreshold = scored.filter((s) => {\n    83→    const sLower = s.text.toLowerCase();\n    84→    return !translationCandidates.some((t) => sLower.startsWith(t.text.toLowerCase()));\n    85→  });\n    86→}\n    87→```\n    88→\n    89→**After:**\n    90→```typescript\n    91→if (translationCandidates.length > 0) {\n    92→  const protectedText = firstStructuralHeading?.text.toLowerCase();\n    93→  scoredForThreshold = scored.filter((s) => {\n    94→    const sLower = s.text.toLowerCase();\n    95→    // Never suppress the structural heading or candidates starting with it\n    96→    if (protectedText && (sLower === protectedText || sLower.startsWith(protectedText + \" \"))) {\n    97→      return true;\n    98→    }\n    99→    return !translationCandidates.some((t) => sLower.startsWith(t.text.toLowerCase()));\n   100→  });\n   101→}\n   102→```\n   103→\n   104→**Impact:** Even if bilingual detection fires incorrectly, the structural heading (computed from embedding quality + structural signals) is preserved. The `firstStructuralHeading` represents the algorithm's best judgment about which ALL_CAPS heading is the recipe title — it should not be overridden by a cosine similarity check against an unvetted position-0 line.\n   105→\n   106→**Risk:** Low. In the legitimate bilingual case (Faszerowana papryka), the structural heading is `\"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\"` — but that case is handled by the position-0 mixed-case title `\"Faszerowana papryka\"` winning via threshold after suppression. The guard would preserve `\"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\"` in `scoredForThreshold`, but since `\"Faszerowana papryka\"` also remains and wins via position factor + being the threshold leader after ALL_CAPS suppression, the final result is unchanged. **Verify this claim by running the test suite.**\n   107→\n   108→**Note on ordering:** Fix B references `firstStructuralHeading`, which is computed at lines 363–370 — before bilingual detection at lines 409–431. The variable is already available. No reordering needed.\n   109→\n   110→---\n   111→\n   112→### Fix C (Defense in depth): Broaden pre-dedup section filter to check all candidates\n   113→\n   114→**Rationale:** The pre-dedup section filter (lines 506–523) correctly identifies `\"CHLEBEK\"` as a section header (ALL_CAPS, followed by ingredient lines). But it only removes it when a longer parent exists in `selected`. If the longer parent was suppressed upstream, the filter is powerless. Checking `rawScored` (all candidates regardless of suppression) makes this filter independently robust.\n   115→\n   116→**Change:** In the pre-dedup section filter (line 516), check `rawScored` instead of `selected` for the longer parent.\n   117→\n   118→**Before (lines 514–521):**\n   119→```typescript\n   120→const candidateLower = candidate.text.toLowerCase();\n   121→const hasLongerParent = selected.some(\n   122→  (other) =>\n   123→    other !== candidate &&\n   124→    other.text.length > candidate.text.length &&\n   125→    other.text.toLowerCase().includes(candidateLower)\n   126→);\n   127→return !hasLongerParent;\n   128→```\n   129→\n   130→**After:**\n   131→```typescript\n   132→const candidateLower = candidate.text.toLowerCase();\n   133→const hasLongerParent = rawScored.some(\n   134→  (other) =>\n   135→    other.text !== candidate.text &&\n   136→    other.text.length > candidate.text.length &&\n   137→    other.text.toLowerCase().includes(candidateLower)\n   138→);\n   139→return !hasLongerParent;\n   140→```\n   141→\n   142→**Impact:** Even when `\"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\"` is absent from `selected` (due to bilingual suppression or any other upstream issue), the filter still sees it in `rawScored` and removes `\"CHLEBEK\"`. This breaks the cascading dependency identified in the feedback.\n   143→\n   144→**Risk:** Low. The filter already requires two conditions: (1) the candidate is ALL_CAPS followed by ingredients, and (2) a longer parent contains it. Checking `rawScored` instead of `selected` only changes _where_ it looks for the parent. False positives would require: an ALL_CAPS section header followed by ingredients, where a longer candidate in `rawScored` contains it as a substring, but the longer candidate is NOT the correct title. This scenario is unlikely — if the longer candidate contains the section header text, it's almost certainly the title that the section header was extracted from.\n   145→\n   146→**Side effect:** If the filter removes `\"CHLEBEK\"` but the full title is also absent from `selected`, the result would fall through to the empty-pool fallback (lines 444–449) or the multi-title guard, both of which would pick the best remaining candidate. This is still better than returning `\"CHLEBEK\"`.\n   147→\n   148→---\n   149→\n   150→## Combined Effect\n   151→\n   152→| Fix | Alone sufficient? | What it prevents |\n   153→|-----|-------------------|------------------|\n   154→| A (pipe filter) | **Yes** for this input | Category headers entering candidate pool |\n   155→| B (structural guard) | **Yes** for this input | Bilingual detection overriding structural heading |\n   156→| C (broader section filter) | **Probably** for this input | Section headers surviving when full title suppressed |\n   157→\n   158→All three together provide three independent layers of protection against the same class of error: upstream suppression of the correct title leaving section headers as the only survivors.\n   159→\n   160→---\n   161→\n   162→## Changes NOT proposed\n   163→\n   164→### Raising the bilingual similarity threshold (0.4 → higher)\n   165→\n   166→Tempting but fragile. The threshold is calibrated for cross-lingual translation pairs (Polish ↔ Korean romanization). Raising it risks breaking the Faszerowana papryka case where suppression of `\"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\"` is correct and necessary. The 0.4 threshold is not the problem — the problem is that the position-0 candidate is not a title at all.\n   167→\n   168→### Making `prePos0` check require title-like characteristics\n   169→\n   170→Could work (e.g., require rawScore > some minimum), but adds another threshold to calibrate and is less transparent than the pipe filter. The pipe filter is a crisp structural signal with no gray area.\n   171→\n   172→### Changing the dedup rule\n   173→\n   174→The dedup rule (\"shorter wins\") is correct and has been stable since iteration 5. The feedback explicitly warns against changing it (line 526–528 comment in code). The issue is not dedup — it's that the correct longer candidate was suppressed before dedup could compare them.\n   175→\n   176→---\n   177→\n   178→## Expected Impact on Accuracy\n   179→\n   180→| Test Case | Current | After Fix |\n   181→|-----------|---------|-----------|\n   182→| ARAYES SHRAK | PASS | PASS (unchanged) |\n   183→| Baked Eggs with Feta... | PASS | PASS (unchanged) |\n   184→| CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM | **FAIL** | **PASS** |\n   185→| Faszerowana papryka | PASS | PASS (verify — Fix B adds structural heading to threshold pool) |\n   186→| FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS | PASS | PASS (unchanged) |\n   187→| Kimchi z ogórków | PASS | PASS (unchanged) |\n   188→| MIXED SEED CRISPBREAD | PASS | PASS (unchanged) |\n   189→| MŁODE PORY DUSZONE W PIWIE | PASS | PASS (unchanged — \"Wiosna\\n/ Warzywa\" has no pipe) |\n   190→| OVERNIGHT STRAIGHT PIZZA DOUGH | PASS | PASS (unchanged) |\n   191→| Pierogi Ruskie | PASS | PASS (unchanged) |\n   192→| SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS... | PASS | PASS (unchanged) |\n   193→\n   194→**Expected accuracy: 100% (all test cases passing)**\n   195→\n   196→---\n   197→\n   198→## Implementation Order\n   199→\n   200→1. **Fix A** — single line addition to `passesHardFilters()`. Run tests.\n   201→2. **Fix B** — 4-line guard in bilingual detection block. Run tests.\n   202→3. **Fix C** — change `selected` → `rawScored` in one `some()` call. Run tests.\n   203→\n   204→All three changes are in `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`. No other files need modification.\n   205→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_013AueKzNjXyX8RXMsYNzzbJ","session_id":"ac343373-92a8-4ed5-8825-039c81cffb50","uuid":"f8a94a93-0b80-4fd3-8f77-8e0192808500"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01UuBvSEXBdHKqYvD8RF72wF","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 12 → 13 Improvement Plan\n     2→\n     3→## Summary\n     4→\n     5→17 failures across 3 patterns, all rooted in two gaps: (1) no bullet-line filter, and (2) incomplete ingredient/section-label detection. Two primary changes fix all 17 failures at the candidate generation stage. Two defense-in-depth changes harden the pipeline against edge cases.\n     6→\n     7→---\n     8→\n     9→## Root Cause Analysis\n    10→\n    11→### Pattern 1: Ingredient bullet lines (12 failures)\n    12→\n    13→Lines like `- 2 jajka`, `- Sól do smaku`, `- Salt to taste` enter the candidate pool because:\n    14→- `passesHardFilters` has no check for bullet-list markers (`- `, `• `)\n    15→- `looksLikeIngredient` only knows English measurement units — misses Polish (`łyżka`, `szklanka`, `szczypta`), compact metric (`100g`, `50ml`), and qualitative patterns (`to taste`, `do smaku`)\n    16→- `startsWithNumber` checks `/^\\s*\\d/` which doesn't match `- 2 jajka` (starts with `- `)\n    17→\n    18→These lines then compete in embedding scoring, where Polish ALL_CAPS titles like \"BARSZCZ CZERWONY\" may have weak similarity to the English-heavy TITLE_REFERENCE. With no structural bonus to save the real title, an ingredient line can win by embedding score alone.\n    19→\n    20→### Pattern 2: Section header `INGREDIENTS` (1 failure — Mozzarella Sticks)\n    21→\n    22→Document structure: `INGREDIENTS` → `MOZZARELLA STICKS` → `- 2 tbsp sugar`. The multi-title guard's `isSubHeader` check examines `sortedCaps.slice(1)` — i.e., everything except the **first** ALL_CAPS heading. It assumes `sortedCaps[0]` is the title. But here `sortedCaps[0]` = `INGREDIENTS` (a section label), so the real title `MOZZARELLA STICKS` gets demoted as a sub-header.\n    23→\n    24→The core issue: section labels like `INGREDIENTS`, `SKŁADNIKI`, `DIRECTIONS`, `PRZYGOTOWANIE` are not recipe titles, but nothing filters them.\n    25→\n    26→### Pattern 3: Compound ingredient joins (4 failures)\n    27→\n    28→When duplicate ingredient lines appear consecutively (`- 100g butter` / `- 100g butter`), `buildCandidates` creates a 2-line join that passes hard filters because `100g` doesn't match any measurement keyword (no bare `g`). With zero ALL_CAPS survivors in `selected`, the `allCapsSelected.length === 0` branch keeps all candidates, producing garbage like `- 100g butter - 100g butter + - Salt to taste`.\n    29→\n    30→This is a downstream consequence of Patterns 1 + 2: if bullet lines and section labels were filtered, the real ALL_CAPS title would survive and the multi-title guard would collapse to the correct result.\n    31→\n    32→---\n    33→\n    34→## Change 1: Bullet-Line Filter in `passesHardFilters`\n    35→\n    36→**Priority:** Critical — fixes 16 of 17 failures directly\n    37→\n    38→**Rationale:** Lines starting with `- ` (hyphen-space), `• ` (bullet), or `* ` (asterisk-space) are list items in recipe documents — always ingredients or instruction steps, never titles. This is a universal structural convention across all languages.\n    39→\n    40→### Code change\n    41→\n    42→**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, function `passesHardFilters`\n    43→\n    44→**Before (lines 138–149):**\n    45→```typescript\n    46→function passesHardFilters(text: string): boolean {\n    47→  if (text.length < 3 || text.length > 80) return false;\n    48→  if (looksLikeIngredient(text)) return false;\n    49→  if (startsWithNumber(text)) return false;\n    50→  if (looksLikeMetadata(text)) return false;\n    51→  if (isLikelyGarbled(text)) return false;\n    52→  // Pipe-separated lines are book category/chapter headers, not recipe titles\n    53→  if (text.includes(\" | \")) return false;\n    54→  // Single-word non-title fragments\n    55→  const words = text.trim().split(/\\s+/);\n    56→  if (words.length === 1 && NON_TITLE_WORDS.has(text.trim().toLowerCase())) return false;\n    57→  return true;\n    58→}\n    59→```\n    60→\n    61→**After:**\n    62→```typescript\n    63→function passesHardFilters(text: string): boolean {\n    64→  if (text.length < 3 || text.length > 80) return false;\n    65→  if (looksLikeIngredient(text)) return false;\n    66→  if (startsWithNumber(text)) return false;\n    67→  if (looksLikeMetadata(text)) return false;\n    68→  if (isLikelyGarbled(text)) return false;\n    69→  // Pipe-separated lines are book category/chapter headers, not recipe titles\n    70→  if (text.includes(\" | \")) return false;\n    71→  // Bullet-list items (ingredients or instruction steps) are never titles\n    72→  if (/^\\s*[-•*]\\s/.test(text)) return false;\n    73→  // Single-word non-title fragments\n    74→  const words = text.trim().split(/\\s+/);\n    75→  if (words.length === 1 && NON_TITLE_WORDS.has(text.trim().toLowerCase())) return false;\n    76→  return true;\n    77→}\n    78→```\n    79→\n    80→### Impact analysis\n    81→\n    82→The regex `/^\\s*[-•*]\\s/` matches lines starting with optional whitespace, then a bullet marker (`-`, `•`, or `*`), then a space. This eliminates:\n    83→\n    84→| Candidate | Match | Effect |\n    85→|---|---|---|\n    86→| `- 2 jajka` | `- ` at start | **Filtered** — fixes Barszcz, Drożdżówki, etc. |\n    87→| `- Sól do smaku` | `- ` at start | **Filtered** — fixes Sernik, Oscypek, Grochówka |\n    88→| `- Salt to taste` | `- ` at start | **Filtered** — fixes Garlic Bruschetta, Spinach Dip, etc. |\n    89→| `- 100g butter` | `- ` at start | **Filtered** — fixes Blackberry Jam, Duck Confit |\n    90→| `- 100g butter - 100g butter` (2-line join) | `- ` at start | **Filtered** — fixes compound joins |\n    91→| `- Sól do smaku + - 2 jajka` (multi-join) | `- ` at start | **Filtered** — fixes Kielbasa, Zupa Żurawina |\n    92→| `BARSZCZ CZERWONY` | No match | Passes ✓ |\n    93→| `Pierogi Ruskie` | No match | Passes ✓ |\n    94→\n    95→**Risk:** Extremely low. Recipe titles never start with `- ` or `• `. The only conceivable edge case is a title starting with `*` (e.g., an OCR artifact for a starred recipe), but `*` followed by a space is standard bullet syntax, not title formatting.\n    96→\n    97→**Why this is placed before `looksLikeIngredient`:** The bullet check is O(1) regex and catches a superset of the ingredient lines that leak through `looksLikeIngredient`. Even if ingredient detection were perfect, bullet filtering is independently valuable as a structural signal.\n    98→\n    99→---\n   100→\n   101→## Change 2: Known Section Label Filter\n   102→\n   103→**Priority:** Critical — fixes 1 failure directly (Mozzarella Sticks), provides defense-in-depth for Pattern 1\n   104→\n   105→**Rationale:** Words like `INGREDIENTS`, `SKŁADNIKI`, `DIRECTIONS`, `INSTRUCTIONS`, `PRZYGOTOWANIE` are universal recipe section headers. They are never recipe titles. Filtering them prevents the `isSubHeader` guard from promoting a section label over the real title.\n   106→\n   107→### Code change\n   108→\n   109→**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n   110→\n   111→Add a new constant and filter check:\n   112→\n   113→```typescript\n   114→/**\n   115→ * Known recipe section labels — these are structural headers, not recipe titles.\n   116→ * Matched case-insensitively after trimming and stripping trailing punctuation (colon, period).\n   117→ */\n   118→const SECTION_LABELS = new Set([\n   119→  // English\n   120→  \"ingredients\", \"directions\", \"instructions\", \"method\", \"preparation\",\n   121→  \"steps\", \"notes\", \"tip\", \"tips\", \"variations\", \"variation\",\n   122→  \"garnish\", \"topping\", \"toppings\", \"frosting\", \"filling\",\n   123→  \"for the sauce\", \"for the filling\", \"for the topping\", \"for the dough\",\n   124→  \"for the crust\", \"for the frosting\", \"for the glaze\",\n   125→  // Polish\n   126→  \"składniki\", \"przygotowanie\", \"sposób przygotowania\", \"sposób wykonania\",\n   127→  \"wykonanie\", \"wskazówki\", \"podpowiedź\", \"warianty\",\n   128→  \"sos\", \"nadzienie\", \"polewa\", \"lukier\", \"ciasto\",\n   129→]);\n   130→\n   131→function isSectionLabel(text: string): boolean {\n   132→  // Strip trailing colon/period, normalize whitespace, lowercase\n   133→  const normalized = text.trim().replace(/[:.]$/, \"\").toLowerCase();\n   134→  return SECTION_LABELS.has(normalized);\n   135→}\n   136→```\n   137→\n   138→Add to `passesHardFilters`:\n   139→\n   140→```typescript\n   141→function passesHardFilters(text: string): boolean {\n   142→  if (text.length < 3 || text.length > 80) return false;\n   143→  if (looksLikeIngredient(text)) return false;\n   144→  if (startsWithNumber(text)) return false;\n   145→  if (looksLikeMetadata(text)) return false;\n   146→  if (isLikelyGarbled(text)) return false;\n   147→  if (text.includes(\" | \")) return false;\n   148→  if (/^\\s*[-•*]\\s/.test(text)) return false;\n   149→  if (isSectionLabel(text)) return false;  // NEW\n   150→  const words = text.trim().split(/\\s+/);\n   151→  if (words.length === 1 && NON_TITLE_WORDS.has(text.trim().toLowerCase())) return false;\n   152→  return true;\n   153→}\n   154→```\n   155→\n   156→### Impact on Mozzarella Sticks\n   157→\n   158→**Before:**\n   159→1. `INGREDIENTS` enters candidate pool, gets ALL_CAPS bonus\n   160→2. `MOZZARELLA STICKS` also enters pool\n   161→3. Multi-title guard: `allCapsSelected = [INGREDIENTS, MOZZARELLA STICKS]`, `sortedCaps[0] = INGREDIENTS`\n   162→4. `isSubHeader` demotes `MOZZARELLA STICKS` → result: `INGREDIENTS`\n   163→\n   164→**After:**\n   165→1. `INGREDIENTS` → `isSectionLabel` = true → **filtered out**\n   166→2. `MOZZARELLA STICKS` enters pool, is the only ALL_CAPS candidate\n   167→3. Multi-title guard: `allCapsSelected.length === 1` → collapses to highest-scoring → `MOZZARELLA STICKS` ✓\n   168→\n   169→### Impact on SKŁADNIKI-first documents (Barszcz, Kielbasa, etc.)\n   170→\n   171→Even without Change 1 (bullet filter), removing `SKŁADNIKI` from the pool prevents it from triggering the multi-title guard. The real title is the sole ALL_CAPS survivor, so the guard collapses correctly. This is why Change 2 provides defense-in-depth for Pattern 1.\n   172→\n   173→### Risk assessment\n   174→\n   175→**False positive risk:** Could a recipe be named \"Ingredients\" or \"Przygotowanie\"? In theory yes, but in practice no — these are generic section labels. The set is conservative (common unambiguous labels only). Multi-word labels like \"for the sauce\" are included because they appear in cookbook sub-section headers and would never be a standalone recipe title.\n   176→\n   177→**Note on trailing punctuation stripping:** Some OCR outputs produce `INGREDIENTS:` or `PRZYGOTOWANIE:` with a colon. The `replace(/[:.]$/, \"\")` ensures these match.\n   178→\n   179→---\n   180→\n   181→## Change 3: Expanded Ingredient Detection (Defense-in-Depth)\n   182→\n   183→**Priority:** Medium — provides backup for edge cases where bullet filter doesn't apply (e.g., ingredient lines without bullet markers in some cookbook formats)\n   184→\n   185→### 3a: Polish measurement units\n   186→\n   187→**Before (lines 20–37):**\n   188→```typescript\n   189→const MEASUREMENT_PATTERNS = [\n   190→  \"cup\", \"cups\", \"tbsp\", \"tsp\", \"tablespoon\", \"teaspoon\",\n   191→  \"oz\", \"lb\", \"gram\", \"grams\", \"kg\", \"ml\", \"liter\",\n   192→  \"pinch\", \"dash\", \"handful\",\n   193→];\n   194→```\n   195→\n   196→**After:**\n   197→```typescript\n   198→const MEASUREMENT_PATTERNS = [\n   199→  // English\n   200→  \"cup\", \"cups\", \"tbsp\", \"tsp\", \"tablespoon\", \"teaspoon\",\n   201→  \"oz\", \"lb\", \"gram\", \"grams\", \"kg\", \"ml\", \"liter\",\n   202→  \"pinch\", \"dash\", \"handful\",\n   203→  // Polish\n   204→  \"łyżka\", \"łyżki\", \"łyżek\",           // tablespoon(s)\n   205→  \"łyżeczka\", \"łyżeczki\", \"łyżeczek\",   // teaspoon(s)\n   206→  \"szklanka\", \"szklanki\", \"szklanek\",     // cup(s)\n   207→  \"szczypta\",                             // pinch\n   208→  \"garść\",                                // handful\n   209→  \"opakowanie\", \"opakowania\",             // package(s)\n   210→  \"plasterek\", \"plasterki\",              // slice(s)\n   211→];\n   212→```\n   213→\n   214→### 3b: Compact metric notation\n   215→\n   216→Add a regex check to `looksLikeIngredient` for patterns like `100g`, `50ml`, `250g`:\n   217→\n   218→**Before (lines 67–70):**\n   219→```typescript\n   220→function looksLikeIngredient(line: string): boolean {\n   221→  const lowerLine = line.toLowerCase();\n   222→  return MEASUREMENT_PATTERNS.some((pattern) => lowerLine.includes(pattern));\n   223→}\n   224→```\n   225→\n   226→**After:**\n   227→```typescript\n   228→function looksLikeIngredient(line: string): boolean {\n   229→  const lowerLine = line.toLowerCase();\n   230→  if (MEASUREMENT_PATTERNS.some((pattern) => lowerLine.includes(pattern))) return true;\n   231→  // Compact metric: \"100g\", \"50ml\", \"250g\" — digit immediately followed by g/ml/kg/l\n   232→  if (/\\b\\d+\\s*(?:g|ml|kg|l)\\b/i.test(line)) return true;\n   233→  // \"to taste\" / \"do smaku\" — qualitative ingredient with no unit\n   234→  if (/\\bto taste\\b/i.test(line) || /\\bdo smaku\\b/i.test(line)) return true;\n   235→  return false;\n   236→}\n   237→```\n   238→\n   239→### Impact\n   240→\n   241→| Line | Before | After |\n   242→|---|---|---|\n   243→| `100g butter` | Not detected (no `gram` keyword) | Detected via `\\b\\d+\\s*g\\b` |\n   244→| `1 łyżka cukru` | Not detected | Detected via `łyżka` in MEASUREMENT_PATTERNS |\n   245→| `Salt to taste` | Not detected | Detected via `\\bto taste\\b` |\n   246→| `Sól do smaku` | Not detected | Detected via `\\bdo smaku\\b` |\n   247→| `50ml mleka` | Not detected | Detected via `\\b\\d+\\s*ml\\b` |\n   248→\n   249→### Risk: false positives on recipe titles\n   250→\n   251→Could `\\b\\d+\\s*g\\b` match a legitimate title? Only if a title contains a number followed by `g`. Examples:\n   252→- \"5g Internet Bread\" — starts with digit → already rejected by `startsWithNumber`\n   253→- \"Bread 500g\" — would be matched, but no real recipe title ends with a weight\n   254→\n   255→Could `\\bto taste\\b` match a title? \"To Taste\" as a recipe name is theoretically possible but not seen in any test corpus. The `\\b` word boundaries prevent partial matches like \"tomato\" or \"toasted\".\n   256→\n   257→---\n   258→\n   259→## Change 4: Harden `startsWithNumber` for Bullet-Stripped Lines (Optional)\n   260→\n   261→**Priority:** Low — fully covered by Change 1, but provides an additional safety net\n   262→\n   263→Currently `startsWithNumber` only checks `/^\\s*\\d/`. After the bullet filter (Change 1), this is adequate. But as defense-in-depth, extend it to also catch digit-first content after a bullet marker:\n   264→\n   265→**Before:**\n   266→```typescript\n   267→function startsWithNumber(line: string): boolean {\n   268→  return /^\\s*\\d/.test(line);\n   269→}\n   270→```\n   271→\n   272→**After:**\n   273→```typescript\n   274→function startsWithNumber(line: string): boolean {\n   275→  // Match lines starting with a digit, or bullet-then-digit (e.g., \"- 2 jajka\")\n   276→  return /^\\s*(?:[-•*]\\s*)?\\d/.test(line);\n   277→}\n   278→```\n   279→\n   280→This catches `- 2 jajka` (digit after bullet) even if the bullet filter were somehow bypassed. Low priority because Change 1 already eliminates all bullet lines.\n   281→\n   282→---\n   283→\n   284→## Expected Impact Summary\n   285→\n   286→| Pattern | Failures | Fix | Confidence |\n   287→|---|---|---|---|\n   288→| Ingredient bullet lines | 12 | Change 1 (bullet filter) | **Very high** — structural signal, no false-positive risk |\n   289→| `INGREDIENTS` section label | 1 | Change 2 (section label filter) | **Very high** — universal convention |\n   290→| Compound ingredient joins | 4 | Change 1 (bullet filter) eliminates both component lines | **Very high** — upstream fix prevents downstream failure |\n   291→| **Total** | **17** | | |\n   292→\n   293→### Regression risk\n   294→\n   295→All changes are **additive filters** in `passesHardFilters` — they only remove candidates that should never have entered the pool. No scoring logic, threshold computation, dedup, or multi-title guard behavior is modified. Existing passing tests are unaffected because:\n   296→\n   297→1. Real recipe titles never start with `- ` / `• ` / `* `\n   298→2. Real recipe titles are never section labels like `INGREDIENTS` or `SKŁADNIKI`\n   299→3. Real recipe titles don't contain compact metric quantities or \"to taste\"/\"do smaku\"\n   300→4. The 80+ currently-passing test cases have none of these patterns as titles\n   301→\n   302→### Performance impact\n   303→\n   304→Zero additional embedding calls. All new checks are O(1) regex or Set lookups executed during candidate generation — well within the 10-second mobile budget. The candidate pool will be *smaller* (fewer false candidates), so embedding calls may actually decrease.\n   305→\n   306→---\n   307→\n   308→## Implementation Order\n   309→\n   310→1. **Change 1** (bullet filter) — single line in `passesHardFilters`, maximum impact\n   311→2. **Change 2** (section labels) — new constant + function + one line in `passesHardFilters`\n   312→3. **Change 3** (expanded ingredients) — extend `MEASUREMENT_PATTERNS` + add regex to `looksLikeIngredient`\n   313→4. **Change 4** (optional `startsWithNumber` hardening) — only if testing reveals edge cases not covered by Changes 1–3\n   314→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_013AueKzNjXyX8RXMsYNzzbJ","session_id":"ac343373-92a8-4ed5-8825-039c81cffb50","uuid":"1cd0467a-deb6-4bc4-a46f-f36b94e9dc25"}
