{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0157E8NfcTj5bX9JpRMFyAFT","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 14 Failure Analysis\n     2→\n     3→## Failure 1: LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA SEEDS\n     4→**Expected:** `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA SEEDS`\n     5→**Got:** `WITH NIGELLA + SEEDS`\n     6→\n     7→### What happened\n     8→\n     9→The true title is spread across 4 lines in the OCR output:\n    10→```\n    11→LABANEH\n    12→BALLS\n    13→WITH NIGELLA\n    14→SEEDS\n    15→```\n    16→\n    17→The algorithm generates joins up to **3 consecutive lines**, so `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA` (3-line join, position 0) is the longest candidate that captures the start of the title. The full 4-word title `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA SEEDS` is never in the candidate pool.\n    18→\n    19→With the full title absent, `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA` (3-line) competes against `WITH NIGELLA` (single, position 2) and `WITH NIGELLA SEEDS` (2-line, position 2). All three are structural headings.\n    20→\n    21→The dedup step then eliminates `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA` because it **contains** `WITH NIGELLA` as a substring, and the dedup rule is \"shorter wins\":\n    22→```\n    23→aLower.includes(b.text.toLowerCase()) && b.text.length < a.text.length\n    24→  → removes \"LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA\" (contains \"with nigella\", shorter)\n    25→```\n    26→\n    27→The structural heading prefix-removal guard (`fshLower.startsWith(sLower + \" \")`) does not help here because `WITH NIGELLA` is a **suffix** of `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA`, not a prefix — so it is not stripped before dedup runs.\n    28→\n    29→After dedup, `WITH NIGELLA` and `SEEDS` remain. Both are all-caps. The multi-title guard checks whether the second candidate (`SEEDS`, position 3) is followed by ingredient-like lines — it is not (body text follows) — so `isSubHeader = false` and both survive. Result: `WITH NIGELLA + SEEDS`.\n    30→\n    31→### Root causes\n    32→1. **3-line join ceiling**: a 4-line title is never formed as a candidate.\n    33→2. **Dedup \"shorter wins\" removes valid longer candidate**: `WITH NIGELLA` is a semantic fragment of the title but dedup treats it as more authoritative than the longer join it partially overlaps.\n    34→\n    35→---\n    36→\n    37→## Failure 2: Smażona zielona fasolka\n    38→**Expected:** `Smażona zielona fasolka`\n    39→**Got:** `GREEN BEANS BORKEUM`\n    40→\n    41→### What happened\n    42→\n    43→The OCR text opens with three title variants:\n    44→```\n    45→Line 0: Smażona zielona fasolka   (Polish, mixed-case — true title)\n    46→Line 1: GREEN BEANS BORKEUM       (English + Korean romanization, all-caps)\n    47→Line 2: 그린빈 볶음                 (Korean script — filtered by garbled check)\n    48→```\n    49→\n    50→`Smażona zielona fasolka` is mixed-case (Polish capitalizes only the first word of a title). It never qualifies as a structural heading (`isAllCaps` strips non-ASCII letters, checks only `[a-zA-Z]`, and `Smażona` contains lowercase ASCII letters).\n    51→\n    52→`GREEN BEANS BORKEUM` is all-caps with 3 words each ≥4 letters → it is a structural heading and receives the +0.10 structural bonus, pushing it above the mixed-case Polish title.\n    53→\n    54→The bilingual-title detection is the intended guard: it looks for a mixed-case candidate at position 0 and a nearby all-caps candidate (position 1–2) with cosine similarity > 0.4. If triggered, it suppresses the all-caps candidate from `scoredForThreshold` (and thus from `selected`).\n    55→\n    56→The guard did **not** trigger here. The Polish phrase `Smażona zielona fasolka` and the English+Korean romanization `GREEN BEANS BORKEUM` are semantically equivalent (both mean \"stir-fried green beans\"), but the embedding similarity falls at or below 0.4. Cross-lingual pairs where one language uses completely different script/word roots (Polish vs. Korean romanization) produce lower cosine similarity than bilingual pairs in related European languages.\n    57→\n    58→### Root causes\n    59→1. **Structural bonus overrides true title**: an all-caps secondary title line wins purely because of the +0.10 structural heading bonus, which mixed-case legitimate titles cannot receive.\n    60→2. **Bilingual detection threshold too strict for cross-linguistic pairs**: 0.4 cosine similarity is not reliably met when Polish and Korean romanization embeddings diverge despite shared meaning.\n    61→\n    62→---\n    63→\n    64→## Common Themes\n    65→\n    66→### 1. All-caps structural heading bias is too strong\n    67→The +0.10 structural bonus is enough to flip the winner when the true title is mixed-case (Polish, Italian, etc. capitalization conventions). Recipes in non-English cookbooks often have mixed-case titles on the first line, followed by an all-caps translation or subtitle.\n    68→\n    69→### 2. Candidate pool limited to 3-line joins\n    70→Titles split across 4+ lines cannot be assembled. This is uncommon but occurs here because the OCR broke `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA SEEDS` into four one-to-two-word lines. The algorithm's pre-merge step only handles lines starting with a continuation character (`/&+:(`), so ordinary word splits across lines are not handled beyond 3.\n    71→\n    72→### 3. Dedup \"shorter wins\" can destroy the best candidate\n    73→The rule is correct for `Pierogi Ruskie` vs `Pierogi Ruskie 200g mąki` but breaks down when a shorter overlapping substring is a fragment of the title rather than a more focused title. `WITH NIGELLA` is not a recipe title — it is an OCR fragment — yet it causes the 3-line join to be eliminated.\n    74→\n    75→### 4. Cross-lingual bilingual detection is fragile\n    76→The 0.4 similarity threshold works for closely related language pairs (e.g. Polish + English, French + English) but is too high for pairs like Polish + Korean romanization. The detection also only looks at position 0 (mixed-case) + positions 1–2 (all-caps). If the all-caps translation appears later, or the Polish title is itself at position 1, the guard does not fire.\n    77→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_013AueKzNjXyX8RXMsYNzzbJ","session_id":"ac343373-92a8-4ed5-8825-039c81cffb50","uuid":"f9d342cb-c047-4f20-9eba-f9e272460074"}
