{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_011kLppwVauPGjBSvtUdgpkg","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have enough context now. Let me outline my proposed changes before writing the plan.\n\n## Key proposed changes\n\n**Failure 1 (LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA SEEDS):** The core issue is that 4-line titles can't be assembled. Rather than simply raising the join ceiling to 4 (which bloats the candidate pool), I propose a **short-line merge pass** before candidate generation: consecutive ALL_CAPS lines where each is ≤2 words get merged into a single logical line. This is different from the existing continuation-character merge — it targets OCR fragmentation of a single heading into multiple short lines. Additionally, the dedup rule needs a guard: never let a substring that starts with a preposition/conjunction (\"WITH\", \"AND\", \"IN\", etc.) eliminate a longer candidate that starts with a content word.\n\n**Failure 2 (Smażona zielona fasolka):** The bilingual detection is too narrow. Instead of relying on cross-lingual embedding similarity (unreliable across distant languages), use a **positional heuristic**: when line 0 is a mixed-case candidate with ≥2 words passing hard filters, and line 1-2 is ALL_CAPS with ≥2 words, treat this as a bilingual header pattern and suppress the ALL_CAPS line's structural bonus. The position-0 mixed-case candidate in a cookbook is almost always the primary title. This avoids the fragile cosine threshold entirely for this specific layout."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":12480,"cache_read_input_tokens":43236,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":12480},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ac343373-92a8-4ed5-8825-039c81cffb50","uuid":"bd6b597e-a9c9-46a6-9825-026669ddd7f7"}
